The '''National Health Action Party''' (NHA) is a political party in [[England]].  Founded by former MP [[Richard Taylor (British politician)|Dr Richard Taylor]] and cancer specialist and chair of the NHS Consultants Association [[Clive Peedell|Dr Clive Peedell]] in May 2012, the party seeks to campaign against changes to the English [[National Health Service (England)|National Health Service]].<ref name=leadnew>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-18062726 |title=Former MP to lead new political party opposed to NHS changes |publisher=bbc.co.uk |work=BBC News|date=14 May 2012 |accessdate=17 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=opposed>{{cite journal|last=Torjesen|first=Ingrid|date=25 May 2012|title=Doctors opposed to NHS reforms set up a new political party|journal=[[BMJ]]|publisher=BMJ Group|location=London|volume=344|page=e3734|issn=1756-1833|doi=10.1136/bmj.e3734|url=http://www.bmj.com/content/344/bmj.e3734|accessdate=19 August 2012}}</ref> The party also intends to follow the recommendations of the [[Health Select Committee]]'s 2009/10 reports,<ref name=opposed/> and campaign on [[Social deprivation|deprivation]], housing, and [[public health]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.pulsetoday.co.uk/newsarticle-content/-/article_display_list/14180919/nhs-party-could-field-50-candidates|title=NHS party ‘could field 50 candidates’|last=Stirling|first=Alisdair|date=28 June 2012|work=Pulse|publisher=Briefing Media|accessdate=19 August 2012|location=United Kingdom}}</ref> The party supports the [[Andrew Dilnot|Dilnot report]]'s recommendations on social care, and believes the [[Stafford Hospital scandal#Public inquiry|Francis report]] has failed to address key problems, such as whistleblower protection and the effect of NHS reforms.<ref name=francis>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalhealthaction.org.uk/francis-report-fails-to-address-root-problems-impossible-targets-inadequate-cash-limits-fragmenting-reforms |title=Francis Report fails to address root problems: impossible targets, inadequate cash limits, fragmenting reforms |date=26 February 2013 |accessdate=13 February 2013}}/</ref>

The party intends to fight in a number of constituencies at the [[Next United Kingdom general election|next general election]], with the aim of replacing MPs who favoured the [[Health and Social Care Act 2012|Health and Social Care Bill]] as well as having significant influence in the event of a [[hung parliament]].<ref name=savenhs>{{cite web|last=Stamp |first=Gavin |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-18077009 |title=Can 'Save NHS' party make an impact at the ballot box? |publisher=bbc.co.uk |work=BBC News|date=22 May 2012 |accessdate=17 June 2012}}</ref> The party plans a [[social media]] campaign and attended the [[Netroots]] conference in June 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/2012/jun/26/national-health-action-social-media|title=National Health Action to launch social media campaign against NHS reforms|last=Taylor|first=Matthew|date=26 June 2012|work=The Guardian|accessdate=19 August 2012}}</ref>

The party was formally launched on 15 November 2012 with a press conference at [[Methodist Central Hall Westminster]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nationalhealthaction.org.uk/news-press/ | title=Press release | publisher=National Health Action Party | accessdate=14 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-20350906 | title=Doctors launch National Health Action party in London |work=BBC News | accessdate=1 December 2012}}</ref> Peedell said that the party aims to win 50 seats at the next general election,<ref>{{cite news | last=
Ramesh|first=Randeep |title=Clive Peedell: a party to save the NHS| date=13 November 2012|publisher=Guardian | accessdate=14 November 2012}}</ref> and was seen as putting pressure on the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] to "repeal the NHS bill".<ref>{{cite news | last=Lees |first=Colin | title=National Health Action is fighting to reclaim the NHS| publisher=Guardian | date=14 November 2012|accessdate=14 November 2012}}</ref>

== Policies ==

* De-commercialisation of the healthcare system, with co-operation rather than competition.
* Neutering of the [[Health and Social Care Act 2012]] and abolition of the costly [[Healthcare in England#Funding and management|purchaser/provider split]].
* Increased public involvement in healthcare, with a reduced reliance on expensive management consultants.
* Improvements to public health, social care, housing and other matters that affect the nation's health.
* A 'new politics' with greater roles for independent candidates and public interests.<ref>[http://www.nationalhealthaction.org.uk/policies/]</ref>

== Supporters ==

* '''Dr Iain Maclennan''', the party's candidate for the [[2013 Eastleigh by-election]], was allowed to run for National Health Action after the local [[Green Party of England and Wales|Green Party]] decided not to contest the election.<ref>{{cite news | url= http://www.nationalhealthaction.org.uk/eastleigh-doctor-challenges-governing-parties/ | title=Eastleigh doctor challenges governing parties | publisher=National Health Action Party | date=8 February 2013}}</ref>
 
* '''Graham Winyard''', previously chairman of the [[Winchester]] [[Liberal Democrats]], defected to National Health Action to support their election campaign in [[Eastleigh]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/defection-mars-lib-dems-fight-for-eastleigh-8488553.html | title=Defection mars Lib Dems' fight for Eastleigh | publisher=Independent | date=10 February 2013|accessdate=13 February 2013}}</ref>

* '''David McCoy''', public health consultant at the Centre for International Health and Development at [[University College London]], has written about the healthcare reforms in ''[[The Lancet]]''<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.opendemocracy.net/ourkingdom/allyson-pollock-david-price-peter-roderick-tim-treuherz-david-mccoy-martin-mckee-lucy-rey | title=The End of the NHS As We Know It? }}</ref> and is a public speaker for the party.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.nationalhealthaction.org.uk/doctors-descending-on-eastleigh-to-support-by-election-candidate/ | title=Doctors descending on Eastleigh to support by-election candidate | publisher=National Health Action | date=15 February 2013|accessdate=15 February 2013}}</ref>

* '''[[Mark Haddon]]''', author of "The Curious Incident of the Dog in the Night Time", criticised the coalition government and has stated that National Health Action is the only party that can be trusted with the NHS.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.nationalhealthaction.org.uk/bestselling-author-mark-haddon-accuses-government-of-dismantling-nhs-and-backs-national-health-action-party/ | title=Bestselling author Mark Haddon accuses government of dismantling NHS and backs National Health Action Party (Press Release) | publisher=National Health Action Party | date=13 February 2013}}</ref>

* '''[[Marcus Chown]]''', science writer and cosmology consultant for [[New Scientist]] magazine, also supports the party.<ref>[http://www.marcuschown.com/COME%20TO%20LAUNCH%20OF%20NATIONAL%20HEALTH%20ACTION%20PARTY.htm|Marcus Chown's website]</ref>

* Actress '''[[Janet Henfrey]]''' and NHS writer/commentator '''Roy Lilley''' have both been seen supporting the party during the [[Eastleigh by-election, 2013|2013 Eastleigh by-election]].

* According to those sites, as of April 2013 the party has around 3,000 followers on '''Facebook'''<ref>{{Facebook|NationalHealthActionParty|National Health Action Party}}</ref> and 8,500 followers on '''Twitter'''.<ref>{{Twitter|NHAparty|National Health Action Party}}</ref>

== Executive Committee ==
<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:IainMaclennanandClivePeedell.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Party co-founder [[Clive Peedell]] (right) canvassing with candidate Iain Maclennan prior to the [[Eastleigh by-election, 2013]].]] -->

* '''[[Richard Taylor (British politician)|Richard Taylor]]''' (party co-founder) was the MP for [[Wyre Forest (UK Parliament constituency)|Wyre Forest]] from 2001-2010 as the [[Independent Kidderminster Hospital and Health Concern]] candidate, and he is the President of Health Concern.<ref name=leadnew/>

* '''[[Clive Peedell]]''' (party co-founder) is a consultant clinical oncologist. He is co-chair of the NHS Consultant's Association and a member of the [[British Medical Association|BMA]] Council. He notably ran 160 miles from Cardiff to London to highlight the [[Health and Social Care Act 2012|Health and Social Care Bill]].

* '''Lucy Reynolds''' (treasurer) is a health policy academic with professional accountancy experience.

* '''Penny Ormerod''' is a freelance journalist who has worked for various large publishers and magazines.

* '''Alastair Fischer''' is a PhD economist who has written a number of papers on [[electoral system]]s.

* '''Guy Baily''' is an [[infectious diseases]] consultant and head of [[HIV]] medicine at the [[Royal London Hospital|Royal London]].

* '''Louise Irvine''' is a [[General Practitioner]] in [[Lewisham]], and is both a member of the BMA Council and programme director for GP training.

* '''Jacky Davis''' is a consultant radiologist, co-chair of the NHS Consultant's Association, and co-founder of Keep Our NHS Public.

* '''Stuart Logan''' is a paediatrician with an interest in childhood disability, and is the Cerebra Professor of Paediatric Epidemiology and Director of Institute of Health Service Research, [[University of Exeter]] Medical School.

* '''John S. Yudkin''' is a retired consultant [[diabetologist]] who was Professor of Medicine at [[University College London]], has experience teaching Global Health, and chairs the International Insulin Foundation charity.

* '''David Lawrence''' is a [[public health]] consultant with experience in commissioning and health services research.<ref name=nhapeople>{{cite web| url=http://www.nationalhealthaction.org.uk/people/ | title=Executive Committee | accessdate=14 February 2013}}</ref>

== Elections contests ==
* [[Eastleigh by-election, 2013]] - placed sixth with 392 votes, roughly 1% of the vote, compared to 32% for the Liberal Democrats (first) and 10% for Labour (fourth).

